segments.text: So that all of the big ones are held in Sabisa in that era?
And then the big ones would be in Sabisa.
It's the biggest building on campus.
And the easiest to clear out and a good floor.
And didn't have air conditioning in those days, and so you just let them go.
You didn't know any difference, so it didn't matter.
Do you remember any...
Any escapades, any real good stories that had anything to do with the dance?
That had anything to do with the dance?
Anything that somebody did after a dance?
No.
I guess we were somewhat normal even for the day then.
You see how far you get with the girl.
Usually not very.
It was expected there was a higher, I think that more was expected of you in those days than there is today.
There were greater expectations of gentlemanliness.
There was no hesitation for mothers to send their daughters to College Station because they're not going to come back pregnant.
They're not going to go down and get drunk out of their mind because that doesn't happen at College Station.
Who chaperoned?
Who policed?
Was there anybody walking around the room checking on behavior?
There may have been.
I wasn't aware they were not visible.
Did you all have alcohol in Sevesa?
No.
We might have taken some in.
It was not supposed to happen, but I'm sure that it did.
Do you remember anybody getting embarrassingly drunk?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
At one time or another, all of us probably got embarrassingly drunk.
Maybe more as a freshman than later on.
And I think that's probably still true in university.
Freshman, fresh out of home, didn't know how to handle it, and he stays drunk far more than a junior or senior.
Right.
Now, in your case, you started dating this special young lady when?
What year?
When you were a junior?
1951, we started dating.
Did you by chance propose to her or get engaged at an Aggie event?
No, it happened up here in Fort Worth.
And we got married in 52.
And she...
We first lived on the campus.
See, I was supposed to graduate in 52, but I had a bad habit of running out of money and not being able to keep going to school.
So I would lay out for a semester in the summer, and I could earn enough money to go back to school for a semester.
So where did y'all live when you were young married?
The first place that we lived was in a garage apartment in Bryan, over near the lake by the golf course.
Somewhere in there, off of one of those streets, we lived in a garage apartment.
And then, the next time we were down, we lived on Eisenhower Street in College Station.
I think that there is a bank or something.
It's just off of University on Eisenhower Street.
I think there's a bank or something right now that would back up to that little house.
And this was a little bitty house.
That house would fit in this room.
What did she do while you were taking classes?
Did she work?
No, she didn't work.
When we went back the second time, we had a child, my oldest daughter.
So she had a little bitty baby.
I remember one time in February, it was College Station.
cold, raining, miserable February.
And we lived in this little wooden house.
And her mother came down.
And Margaret was just crawling.
just barely crawling, maybe pulling up a little bit.
And she was in that cold, damp house, barefoot, with nothing but a diaper on.
And her mama drove up in her brand new, big, long Cadillac automobile and came in and said, jumped on us and up that child.
Where's the child going to die?
What do you think?
Let me get some shoes on.
She outgrew her shoes, and we don't have any money, and we can't buy shoes.
She's just going to have to suck it up.
Ooh, that woman was mad.
Well, that kid had shoes that afternoon, I'll guarantee you.
Had everything that she could buy in the city of Bryan.
Oh, she got mad at me, and she talked bad, too.
Was there any kind of social activity for student wives?
Nothing special.
No.
There was no student wives organization.
The interesting thing is there were a lot of us who knew each other and who became friends.
And so, again, on football weekends, you would assemble at one or the other houses.
As I say, our entire house was about a big group.
And yet we could get those girls with those great big dresses and you'd just put them around the walls, you understand.

because of big old dresses and we could get five or six of them in there let's see let's go back to student organizations uh singing cadets were they saying cadets cadets were there the aggie players were there the uh there were there were organizations
from almost each department, plus clubs of all types.
What were hometown clubs for?
It was really to cushion for the newcomers.
More than a bunch of hometown people getting together across the hometown.
It was a cushion for the kid who's just coming down there.
Whether he's entered as a freshman, sophomore, junior, senior, it doesn't matter.
Was it a ride-back-home organization also?
I guess to a degree.
Most of us just went over by the Safeway store and hitchhiked.
Describe that routine.
I always hitchhiked to the north.
And you got...
You've got to ride up to the Safeway store in Bride, which is where Highway 21 crosses 6.
How would you get, though, from the campus to there?
The best way you could.
However, if you hitchhike, you didn't accept a ride past that hitchhike point.

If somebody says, well, I'm going all the way to Fort Worth, I'd have to say, well, thank you very much, sir, but you need to let me out there, and I bet there's one of those guys who wants to go to Fort Worth.
And that was just the etiquette of hitchhiking.
Now, what did you wear?
Uniform.
That'll get you right.
Did you put your thumb up?
Of course.
Only one person.
There may be 20 people standing on the corner, but one person holds his thumb.
All right.
And who got to be first in line?
The man holding his thumb.
And then the next man in line is the man.
But what made him first?
Because he was there first.
Rank had nothing to do with it.
No, rank had nothing to do with it.
Did you all drop handles while you were waiting?
Yes.
Okay.
And was it normal for the car to stop, the vehicle to stop and give only one person a ride?
No, I've seen the person by themselves take three, four, you know, whatever they could get in the car.
Cars were big in those days.
Now, you were coming, say, to Fort Worth.
Where did you catch a ride out of Fort Worth to go back?
Was there a special place?
Yes, it was on the south side of Fort Worth on Hemphill Avenue, and I can't tell you exactly where it was, but it was an accepted, appointed place.
I could probably drive down there and find it.
By and large, were the only people standing at that place Aggies?
Yes.
Do you remember any goofy...
humorous hitchhiking experiences?
Not for me.
I always got good rides.
I never did get with any weird people.
Never did run into anything like that.
It just so happened I didn't.
Did you ever hear of anybody who had a truly bad experience?
Oh, yeah.
I've heard of them who would get with drunks and get scared out of their wits and so forth.
That was, I suppose, the most common thing.
I got a ride.
This guy was so drunk he couldn't stay on the road.
But you don't remember anybody being robbed?
No.
No.
No.
Don't know of anything.
Let's see.
Other organizations.
RVs?
Oh, sure.
Ross Wilde here has been there forever.
Was that important?
They were one of those elite organizations, and those were the dedicated
military people.
Single?
Not married?
Oh, yes.
Not married.
Single.
Dedicated.
They were there.
They didn't care so much about the degree.
They wanted the commission.
Did you all use the phrase, gun home?
I don't remember the use of it.
We used the phrase, you know, he's a classic courtier.
As you get on to be a senior, a lot of us...
As a matter of fact, during my junior year was one of those times I had to drop out.
Simply didn't have any money.
And so I had to get out and go to work.
And because I was forced to break, Korea is just over.
And because I was forced to break of my service,
The Army didn't want any more second lieutenants and they didn't find any reason in the world to break the contract.
And so they did.
So you're not in the Corps all of... No.
And again, it was a condition of the times.
The Army was looking to get rid of lieutenants.
They didn't want any more lieutenants.
It was for the convenience of both of us that the contract was terminated.
What was the most prestigious student leadership positions?
Well, the President's Student Body and Yellow Leader.
Those were the... That was bigger than Corps Commander?
Corps Commander was important to the Corps, but again, let's look back at post-World War II and post-Korea.
The civilian population was growing
rapidly.
People who did not, although corps was required of high school graduates entering as freshmen, anybody with a military record was not required to go into the corps and they didn't want any more army.
So those people were increasing in volume and so it was increasingly
I'm moving to its position, I guess, that it has achieved today, where it's important.
But to the overall, it's not as important, probably, as the political office is.
What can you share, any information you know from any source about secret fraternities?
One of my roommates was a member of the True Texans.
So it did exist?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
About how many members were there?
Fewer than 100.
At one time?
Yes.
Oh, okay.
Yes.
And he was a member.
And we kidded him about it.
It wasn't a big deal to me.
Bob was a member of it.
And so what?
Bob was politically active.
And so it existed.
What was their purpose?
Social.
They weren't trying to.
They had no agenda that I was aware of.
And certainly, I was within arm's length of it.
Were they trying to get their members involved?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
They wanted their people to be the political people.
That's what I thought.
Yes.
They made sure that their people
were running for the elective offices and they made sure that
they made the signs, gave the support, blah, blah, blah.
And 90% of that is what name do you recognize, and that's who you vote for.
You didn't listen to speeches and decide this is the best man for it.
It was recognition, which they knew, so they flooded and generally achieved that.
So they had some success.
Oh, yes.
And did that include Corps Commander and
Head yell leader?
I think it got so that, yes, it did include the yell leader.
But I think it, because the corps commander was selected internally by the administration, it was less there, although my roommate was an adjutant on corps staff.
At what point in his four years, as far as you know, did he become a member?
His junior year.
As far as you know, was that when they were selected?
Did it matter Army, Air Force, Corps?
Or not Corps.
It happened mostly within the Corps.
His car for me and went off in my car, which is air conditioned.
And he said, your car needs gas.
I knew that when he left.
And he's appearing right now in Henry V. He's rehearsing As You Like It.
They're doing Henry V and rehearsing As You Like It.
They'll follow Henry V as you like it.
As far as you know, did many other people know who were members of the TTs?
I think everybody who was close to a member knew more than one member.
When it blew up, when the thing blew up at the university.
When was that?
At that time I was, at that time my roommate was the editor of the battalion.
His name was Frank Menezes.
And when it first came out was that semester that Frank and I were living together.
And Frank really said, you know, there's a good story here, but he didn't think it was worth anything.
It became, it became a big deal for one reason or another to the administration.
So this is the early 50s?
Yes.
It became
became a big deal to the administration.
And was probably a bigger deal to them.
The back, Frank really, you know, it was page three stuff.
We could get weak.
When it was quiet on the campus, that might be page three and Frank and I would sit and make up things to go on page one.
Did anything happen to the team members?
Yes.
Bob was on core staff and he was busted.
As were all of them.

yes they were all busted because that was a prohibited to have a secret because of the secrecy and as far as anybody knew how long had the tts been in existence i have no idea but it's been a long time i don't know either i think it was was there any other as far as you know there was none other than i was aware of have you ever heard anybody talk about the stickers apparently back in maybe even in the 20s there was
And the name may have come from the word swastika.
No brown shirts.
No, no, no.
It predates.
Predates that?
Yes.
In the 20s, you see, the Nazi party didn't.
That's right.
The Navajo symbol for friendship was the swastika.
And if you look through some early 20s,
Longhorn, yearbooks, you'll see a cage or a swastika?
Here and there.
Here and there.
I was not aware of that.
All right.
So do you know whether the TTs existed after the early 50s?
They busted everybody, but the organization being independent, to the best of my knowledge, continued to be secret and they continued to associate with one another.
I don't think they had formal bylaws.
I don't think they had, I think they had loose group agendas.
And I think that that continued.
I don't believe that, at least for the time I was there, I don't, they injured them as individuals and the hope was, I guess, to put fear into it.
But, and dissuade other people from doing this.
But as long as I was there, I think they existed.
All right, let's go back now to your first year or two.
You didn't have a car.
About how often did you go back and forth from home and how?
I went home for Christmas.
Thanksgiving?
No.
Really?
No, but my freshman year, I think we played a game, College Station.
So I didn't go home.
But I went home for Christmas.
And I didn't go home that much.
I personally didn't go home that much.
Do you remember having a date your freshman year?
No.
What about sophomore year?
Not many.
How did you get a date?
Usually through a friend.
He knows somebody in his hometown.
Like this special young lady?
He has a girlfriend at home and she has a friend.
Like this special young lady who would mean so much to you.
Did you know her?
How did you meet her?
That way.
A friend of mine.

had a had an aggie friend yes and she had a friend and uh it was court trip and uh that's how to fort worth no portrait actually oh okay i described the routine of the court trip either to any of the four oh you'd leave leave what what time and how did you get there well you got there the best way you could
For you, what was that?
Well, that was hitchhiking.
Again, not uncommon.
Simply not uncommon.
You got there as best you could.
You usually were able to get there by Friday night.
And you then tried to find a place to stay.
If somebody had a room, that usually meant 30 people could sleep, you see.

Then there was the parade in the morning, and the game, and then everybody started, if you didn't have a date, you started trying to get out there, because there's a hell of a lot of people going to be hitchhiking going back.
Now, usually within your outfit you had two or three guys from the big cities, or maybe four or five or more.
And they had access to automobile once they got to the city.
And that was how you got around.
You stayed at homes, you stayed a little bit of everywhere.
Can you describe how you met this young lady then?
All right.
My friend was going with a girl from Fort Worth and she had this friend.
And we, he said, I can get, he arranged the date.
I don't know whether it was at my insistence or at his, I don't remember.
But at any rate, the date would be in Dallas, and she was going to TCU, but she was going to stay with a friend at SMU.
And so we met, and we went to the game, and we were going out after the game, and I don't remember we were going somewhere.
You're a sophomore?
No, I'm a junior.
Yeah, I'm a junior.
And we had a good time.
We enjoyed each other.
We had a lot of fun and decided we wanted to see each other some more.
It was a typical weekend.
She got back a little bit late to the SMU dorm, but managed to get in through a window which was
Everybody used it.
It was the highway even for the girls that lived in the dorm.
And then we met the next day and came to Fort Worth.
And I met her parents who lived across the street from the girl the other guy was going with.
And they invited me back the next weekend for some purpose, which escapes me.
I don't remember, but it was something significant.
And so I came back the next weekend and stayed with her at her home.
And then I always had a place to stay.
Did the Aggies in that game, that first day, did the Aggies score any touchdowns?
So did this guy get to kiss his date at the first game?
I'm sure we must have.
I don't know that for sure because that was not during A&M's high departure period.
And Kyle Rook was playing for the Mustangs in that era, I think.
That's about 51 or 52.
No, it's worse than that.
It's Don Meredith.
So did we score anything?
I don't know.
I wouldn't be absolutely certain about that.
Let's see.
Meredith and Bob Lilly was playing for TCU, so it wasn't a good time to be an Aggie.
We didn't win a lot in those days.
Campus characters, was Pinky around then?
Pinky was around, not what Pinky was later on, but Pinky was on campus, yes.
Lou, old Army Lou?
Lou, Lou, you bet.
Trade with Lou, he's right with you, yes sir.
Lou, he helped everybody.
Yes, he bought books from Lou, because you get them cheaper, Lou's, he'd always buy back.
Were there any off-campus events in the United States or in the world
during your student years that you remember caused you concern?
Like was there anything going on in the Far East during that time?
Well, Korea existed during that period of time, and that was of concern to us of cannon fodder age.
But that's really all that was going on in the world that was of concern was Korea.
But you were aware of your draft status?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Yes, you knew absolutely.
You had a student deferment.
Did that have any encouragement to you to stay in school and keep making your grades?
No, that was not significant to me.
Yes, that would not have made a difference to me.
There weren't any assassinations or bombings?
No, no big deals like that.
Sure, atomic weapons tests were going on, but we didn't think anything of that.
That was just an interesting thing.
Were there any great personalities that visited A&M during your days?
Well, of course, we didn't have a president on campus during my four years.
We had a governor.
I think we did a parade for the governor, but what the hell do you see from the parade?
What was his name?
I don't remember.
Shivers?
Shivers may have been governor.
I don't recall.
But we would have, yes, the Corps would have passed and reviewed for him, but that would be about as close as you got.
What were the most popular student indulgences at the time?
Beer.
Where'd you get it?
out of Brazos County and bring it in.
Where?
Generally, just as quick as you can get across the Brazos River.
And what was... Farm Road 60 going to Snoop, was it called Whiskey Bridge?
Yes, yes, Whiskey Bridge.
But beer was the big thing because it was cheap.
Do you remember what label, what variety?
Oh, yes.
You drank Schlitz and Southern Select and Pearl.
Grand Prize?
I wasn't a Grand Prize drinker.
You're not an old man.
No.
Oh, is that right?
John Lindsay's.
John Lindsay.
Sarah.
Sarah.
Sarah's.
Was hard liquor still there, Uncle Ed's?
Yes.
Can you describe Uncle Ed's?
No, I'm sorry, just another place.
Nothing outstanding stands out.
And was there a gravel pit or a... Clay pits.
Clay pits.
That's where you went to do your drinking and you could swim in the clay pits.
Where was it?
down Welburn Road a little ways and off toward the river.
And it was exactly that.
It was old where it had been dug out and the water filled back in and gave a nice place to swim.
And away from everybody where you weren't hassled for drinking beer and browsing.
Did male and female ever go out there?
Oh, yeah.
Did they wear bathing suits, or was there sometimes skinny dipping?
Well, I never did see a girl skinny dipping.
I would have remembered that.
I never did see girls, I'm sure.
And I didn't myself.
I wore swimsuits and plate bits.
Smoking.
What were people smoking?
Tobacco.
What kind of, what labels?
Oh.
Bell Mel.
And the old traditionals never were big.
Camels and Lucky Stripes and so forth were never big use things.
It was usually the lighter tobaccos that were important.
And the one name comes to mind, I guess it's because that's what I smoked.
And do you remember anybody chewing or dipping snuff?
Few people dipped snuff, not much chewing.
Nobody smoked a pipe.
None of the students.
Not people that I was familiar with.
Did you all even know the word marijuana?
Marijuana, that's interesting.
Marijuana was not illegal.
And marijuana was not something anyone who is anybody would
